snippet.textDisplay:
Loving the videos both from here and on LInus Tech Tips, but here's some production advice for the future:
I'm aware you use a teleprompter in your studios, and in doing this you should have the exact script that is spoken in the video, so why don't you use that to make accurate subtitles for your videos rather than relying on the (occasionally inaccurate) auto-generator.
To make things even easier, YouTube has a feature where you can transcribe (or simply just copy in from the transcoder files) the text that you have spoken, and YouTube will automatically set the timings for the subtitles. Neat!
snippet.textOriginal:

Do we really need this? I'm happy with 1920*1080... and I have played on 4K monitors at various stores and see no difference between HD and 4KHD playing the bulk of games, other than what? Yeah: Lower frame rates.
Not a good trade-off.
What we need today? For game companies to step back and say "Okay... let us rethink. Is it the 'uber-visuals' that sell a game or good gameplay? Of course, it is the latter!"
